1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {The most popular reply to 2.Nf3, seeking to play the
Najdorf Variation among other things @@StartBracket@@the main point behind 2...
d6 is to prepare the move Nf6 without getting hit by 3.e5 as in the romantic
Nimzowitch Variation that you can practice down below@@EndBracket@@ *Honorable
mention to the Dragon fans out there!} 3. d4 {Striking for quick development,
fooling everyone that we are going to play the Open Sicilian for one move!
Little do they know that they are running in to our sneaky and slightly
forgotten Hungarian Variation!} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {Voila!The Hungarian Variation is
on the board, breaking all the opening principles as early as move 4, but hey,
we need to adapt to modern chess. Anish Giri already showed why 4.Nxd4 is no
longer a problem in his Najdorf course, so who am i to argue with that?} Nc6 {
The principled move, attacking the early developed Queen.} 5. Qe3 {Moving the
Queen once again instead of developing the Bishop to b5!A very fresh approach
that started to pick up in 2018! While Steinitz is probably turning in his
grave watching me recommend this, the top GrandMaster and beautiful chessable
author Harikrishna Pentala @@StartBracket@@world no. 21 at the moment of
making this course@@EndBracket@@ used it no less than 11 times in his recent
games @@StartBracket@@dated 2018-2020@@EndBracket@@. Now that you have a
strong background of the line, let me briefly introduce you to the main ideas
behind this system: -against g6 White always plays: Be2, 0-0, Ph3, Rd1, Nc3
@@StartBracket@@with annoying e5 ideas@@EndBracket@@ -against e6/e5 White
always plays: Be2, 0-0, Rd1, Pc4!, Nc3 @@StartBracket@@with the rock solid
Maroczy Bind@@EndBracket@@} Nf6 {Is the most natural place for the Knight and
what you are going to encounter in most of your games.} 6. Be2 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8.
h3 {Stopping any Bg4/Ng4 ideas.} O-O 9. Rd1 {Creating an unpleasant pin over
the d file and threatening to kick the enemy Knight with e5 in some positions.}
Nd7 {Black is sidestepping any e5 ideas and this move is also directed against
one of our main plans of going Qf4-Qh4 because Black will have the strong
reaction of Nde5!The drawback for this plan is that the c8 Bishop will have to
fianchetto on b7 and Black is no longer controlling the d5 square, which means
that we can use it for our Knight!} 10. Nc3 {Against this particular line with
9...Nd7 we can simply solve the problem of our c1 Bishop by going for the
Fianchetto! Then our simple plan is to defend the Bishop on b2 with Rb1, play
a3 just for safety measures so black is not getting any Nb4 counterplay and we
are ready to jump with the Knight on d5!} b6 {Trying to develop the Queen-Side.
} 11. b3 {This move has been played succesfuly by Anton Demchenko against one
of the biggest experts of the Sicilian from the Black side, Alexei Sarana.The
point is to develop the Bishop to b2, and after defending it with the move Rb1,
White can jump on d5 with the Knight, putting annoying pressure on Black's
position.} Bb7 12. Bb2 Nc5 13. a3 {Small profilaxis, avoiding Nb4 ideas, and
maybe even considering to play b4 ourselves.} Qc8 14. Rab1 {Defending the
Bishop, preparing to jump with the Knight on d5.} Ne5 {Black should aim for
exchanges since his position is lacking space this will give the rest of his
pieces more room to breathe @@StartBracket@@will it be enough
tho?@@EndBracket@@.} 15. Nd5 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bxd5 17. Bxg7 {An important small
detail to bring Black's King on g7 so you can either check on d4 or Rook lift
Rd4-Rh4 with a tempo.} Kxg7 18. exd5 {Capturing this way to fix the weakness
on e7 and prepare the rook lift via-d4.} Re8 19. Rd4 {White is much better
here since you can press on the e7 pawn and switch to the King-side with Rh4
whenever you feel like it's the good time.As an aditional idea you could
consider advancing your pawn to h5 trying to weaken Black's Queen-Side even
more.Note that Black's only pawn break is e5 but that will always increase
your Bishop's strength and create aditional weaknesses.} *

