1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Seeking to play the Sveshnikov, this move has been the
Main Weapon of the Current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen in his World
Championship Match against Fabiano Caruana in London 2018.} 3. Bb5 {Going for
the Rossolimo Attack! This is considered to be the most painful move for Black
from a theoretical point of view nowadays and also what Fabiano Caruana used
against Magnus Carlsen in their World Championship Match in 2018 to get
promising positions from the opening, even though he could not convert it in
the end. From a practical perspective i think this will help a lot of club
players as well @@StartBracket@@not only the Top Grand Masters@@EndBracket@@
from a number of reasons: -this is a lifetime ever-green opening, always full
of new ideas @@StartBracket@@keeping me busy update the course all the
time@@EndBracket@@ -easy to grasp -it is a plan based opening
@@StartBracket@@you can play this without relying on move by move
preparation@@EndBracket@@} g6 4. Bxc6 {Not the only move in the position, but
the most abitious one in my opinion and the favorite line of world's biggest
Rossolimo expert, Fabiano Caruana @@StartBracket@@world no.2-rated 2823 by the
time of making this course@@EndBracket@@. Before moving on let's see the
bright side behind this decision: -black will have doubled pawns
@@StartBracket@@a long term weakness@@EndBracket@@ -we are defining the pawn
structure very early on in the game, taking a lot of options away from our
opponent -we have a very clear game plan against both 4...dxc6 and 4...bxc6}
bxc6 {Is leading to dynamic play. Personally, i used to hate facing this until
i found:} 5. d4 {First of all, you may be wondering WHAT ON EARTH IS THIS?! So
i was! And 3 days later i was playing the line myself in the World
Championship U18 in Porto Carras @@StartBracket@@There is a funny story about
how i found this line in the model games chapter of the main
course@@EndBracket@@.} Bg7 6. dxc5 {Taking the pawn, inviting Black to develop
the Queen if he wants it back.} Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 {The best way to block the check,
supporting the pawn push to c4 in some lines, and making room for Rb1-Pb4.} Ba6
{A total of 26 games out of 47 with this move!} 8. Rb1 {Threatening to play b4.
} Qxa2 {Looks very tempting at first, keeping White's King in the center, but
the situation is very tricky for Black.This is the perfect scenario for us to
trap our opponent:} 9. b4 {Now Black has to face the surprising maneuver of
Rb3-Ra3 hitting both the a6 Bishop and the Queen. This is already too late for
Black to recover, and only thing he did... was playing principled moves!} Bb5
10. Rb3 {Preparing Ra3, to attack the Queen.} Nf6 11. Ra3 {Attacking the Queen.
} Qe6 12. c4 {Attacking the Bishop.} Bxc4 {This might seem to save Black for
the time being but here is the main point:} 13. Ng5 {Getting rid of the key
defender of the c4 Bishop! Now the Queen has to move but the Bishop will be
lost.} Qe5 14. Nxc4 {The hidden point and what a lot of players will miss from
far away is that after playing 14.Nxc4 suddenly the Knight from g5 will be
defended by the c1 Bishop.Quite a deadly trap i would say!} *

