1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Seeking to play the Sveshnikov, this move has been the
Main Weapon of the Current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen in his World
Championship Match against Fabiano Caruana in London 2018.} 3. Bb5 {Going for
the Rossolimo Attack! This is considered to be the most painful move for Black
from a theoretical point of view nowadays and also what Fabiano Caruana used
against Magnus Carlsen in their World Championship Match in 2018 to get
promising positions from the opening, even though he could not convert it in
the end. From a practical perspective i think this will help a lot of club
players as well @@StartBracket@@not only the Top Grand Masters@@EndBracket@@
from a number of reasons: -this is a lifetime ever-green opening, always full
of new ideas @@StartBracket@@keeping me busy update the course all the
time@@EndBracket@@ -easy to grasp -it is a plan based opening
@@StartBracket@@you can play this without relying on move by move
preparation@@EndBracket@@} g6 4. Bxc6 {Not the only move in the position, but
the most abitious one in my opinion and the favorite line of world's biggest
Rossolimo expert, Fabiano Caruana @@StartBracket@@world no.2-rated 2823 by the
time of making this course@@EndBracket@@. Before moving on let's see the
bright side behind this decision: -black will have doubled pawns
@@StartBracket@@a long term weakness@@EndBracket@@ -we are defining the pawn
structure very early on in the game, taking a lot of options away from our
opponent -we have a very clear game plan against both 4...dxc6 and 4...bxc6}
dxc6 {The most popular recapture leading to more of a positional battle.This
is considered to be the best line for Black from a theoretical point of view,
but the general feeling is that White gets a plesant position without doing
anything crazy.} 5. d3 {Against 4...dxc6 this is what we are always looking
forward to.We want to play it slow with 5.d3 and then we will play the
prophylactycal move 6.h3 @@StartBracket@@trying to avoid Bg4
ideas@@EndBracket@@.Notice that the character of the position is pretty slow
now thanks to the lack of pawn breaks in the center, and we can afford making
this preparatory moves before starting to develop the rest of our pieces.The
main point behind starting this way is that we know for sure that d3 and h3
will fit very well on the board, and we are waiting a bit to see how Black
wants to play this.Once we collect some informations about his set-up we can
pick our best plan according to his play.This flexible approach has been
causing a lot of pain for the Black players recently.} Bg7 6. h3 e5 {Used to
be a popular way of playing for Black and still something that you are quite
likely to face.The problem of this line is that White can grab the initiative
very early on in the game on the Queen-Side.} 7. a4 {Thanks to Lc0 this move
has become very popular nowadays in this Rossolimo structure. While some time
ago everyone was more or less automatically going for the a3-b4 plan this is
the modern way of handling things on the Queen-Side.White is simply
threatening to grab even more space with a5 and then to attack the c5 pawn
with Be3, making it really awkward for Black to defend it.} a5 {The standard
reaction, limiting White's play.} 8. Na3 {The Knight is heading now to the c4
square, from where it exerts a lot of pressure over the e5 pawn, but also
putting pressure on the Queen-Side @@StartBracket@@White has a great trap that
you need to know@@EndBracket@@ so watch carefully:} b6 {A standard move to
keep the Queen-Side together.} 9. Nc4 {Already creating a threat of capturing
the e5 pawn.} f6 10. Be3 {Now that there is no f5 approaching, we can develop
the Bishop safely.} Be6 11. Nfd2 {This is a very important move, preparing to
recapture on c4 with the Knight and it is also setting up one of the most
aesthetic pawn breaks in chess @@StartBracket@@no exaggeration
here@@EndBracket@@} Ne7 12. b4 {The enemy Queen-Side was looking so solid, but
in reality it's so fragile!After this marvelous shot, Black's Queen-Side will
be left in ruins.} axb4 {12...cxb4 Does not help Black's situation because of:
13.Bxb6} 13. a5 {Undermining the c5 pawn by sacrificing yet another one! It
does look like quite a big investment at first but you can think about it like
buying a Bitcoin while it was still worth 100$...} bxa5 14. Bxc5 O-O 15. Ra4 {
White will play Qa1 next and start picking up the Queen-Side pawns.You can
also take your time and castle short, there is no rush because Black has no
way to escape this painful situation.} *

