the most abitious one in my opinion and the favorite line of world's biggest
Rossolimo expert, Fabiano Caruana @@StartBracket@@world no.2-rated 2823 by the
time of making this course@@EndBracket@@. Before moving on let's see the
bright side behind this decision: -black will have doubled pawns
@@StartBracket@@a long term weakness@@EndBracket@@ -we are defining the pawn
structure very early on in the game, taking a lot of options away from our
opponent -we have a very clear game plan against both 4...dxc6 and 4...bxc6}
dxc6 {The most popular recapture leading to more of a positional battle.This
is considered to be the best line for Black from a theoretical point of view,
but the general feeling is that White gets a plesant position without doing
anything crazy.} 5. d3 {Against 4...dxc6 this is what we are always looking
forward to.We want to play it slow with 5.d3 and then we will play the
prophylactycal move 6.h3 @@StartBracket@@trying to avoid Bg4
ideas@@EndBracket@@.Notice that the character of the position is pretty slow
now thanks to the lack of pawn breaks in the center, and we can afford making
this preparatory moves before starting to develop the rest of our pieces.The
main point behind starting this way is that we know for sure that d3 and h3
will fit very well on the board, and we are waiting a bit to see how Black
wants to play this.Once we collect some informations about his set-up we can
pick our best plan according to his play.This flexible approach has been
causing a lot of pain for the Black players recently.} Bg7 6. h3 Nf6 {Black's
most popular choice, preparing to either castle short, or to stay flexible
with Nd7 and e5.} 7. Nc3 Nd7 {The Knight is preparing to embark on the long
and luxurious journey to d4 via f8-e6.} 8. Be3 e5 {This is how ''the cool
kids'' play this line.Black is no longer rushing to castle short because he
can go on the other side of the board for a more double-edged fight.} 9. Qd2 {
Developing the Queen on the natural square, while threatening to play Bh6 and
get rid of the Bishop Pair. At first the Bishop on g7 might not look very
impressive but you should never underestimate the power of the Bishop Pair!
For more tips on that make sure to check the chapter on the Accelerated Dragon
because i am explaining in great depth what you need to do in order to
maximize the potential of the Bishop Pair.} h6 {Stopping White from playing
Bh6.} 10. O-O {Now that there is no other useful move to make, we are going to
castle.Notice that we could afford delaying castling for a few moves because
there is nothing going much in the center, but generally you should be very
careful about your King safety! @@StartBracket@@take that as a friendly
reminder from someone that got checkmated a lot@@EndBracket@@.} b6 {The modern
way of handling this line, implemented by Magnus Carlsen. Black is defending
the b6 pawn so that the Knight can embark to his costy journey to the d5
square @@StartBracket@@via f8-e6@@EndBracket@@ without having to worry about
defending the c5 pawn. Here i recommend going for the Nh2-f4 Black, since the
a3-b4 plan has been refuted by the current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen
@@StartBracket@@amongst others@@EndBracket@@ in his game against Wang Hao.
Black simply ignored White's play on the Queen-side and went Nf8-Ne6 and
sacrificed a pawn on the Queen-side to gain the initiative with f5.} 11. Nh2 {
We are sticking with the standard plan of going Nh2 and f4 because we already
know that if we go for a3-b4 it's not going to end well...} Nf8 {The Knight
starts its journey to d4.} 12. f4 {Going for our main pawn lever, this is the
reason why we have played the move 11.Nh2.} exf4 13. Bxf4 {We always take on
f4 with the Bishop! In case you were wondering Rxf4 is playable, but you don't
get any additional options other than playing Rf2 when Black goes Ne6 and even
in that case it does not seem like the greatest achievment. Instead it is much
better to take with the Bishop on f4 and then you can either retreat on e3 or
g3, depending on the situation.} Ne6 {By far the best move, because it's
forcing us to play Be3 otherwise Black get's a good position after Qg5!} 14.
Be3 {We prefer to go Bg3 in general to have e5 ideas, but in this particular
line Black will have great counterplay based on 14...Qg5. I explained the
details in great depth in the main course so you may be considering to have a
look on that.} Nd4 15. Rae1 {The most aggressive, and the best continuation in
my opinion!White is playing for e5 and Ne4 ideas.} Be6 {Preparing to go long
castle.} 16. e5 {Threatening to play Ne4.} Nf5 17. Bf2 {The only square for
the Bishop, because Bf4 was running into g5.} Qc7 {The best square for the
Queen, attacking e5.} 18. Nf3 {Defending e5, preparing to play Ne4.} O-O-O 19.
Ne4 {With b4 to come next, i like White's chances of a Queen-Side attack.} *

