1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Seeking to play the Sveshnikov, this move has been the
Main Weapon of the Current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen in his World
Championship Match against Fabiano Caruana in London 2018.} 3. Bb5 {Going for
the Rossolimo Attack! This is considered to be the most painful move for Black
from a theoretical point of view nowadays and also what Fabiano Caruana used
against Magnus Carlsen in their World Championship Match in 2018 to get
promising positions from the opening, even though he could not convert it in
the end. From a practical perspective i think this will help a lot of club
players as well @@StartBracket@@not only the Top Grand Masters@@EndBracket@@
from a number of reasons: -this is a lifetime ever-green opening, always full
of new ideas @@StartBracket@@keeping me busy update the course all the
time@@EndBracket@@ -easy to grasp -it is a plan based opening
@@StartBracket@@you can play this without relying on move by move
preparation@@EndBracket@@} e6 {This is known to be a very dynamical line used
with great succes by incredibly tactical-gifted players such as Boris Gelfand,
Alexei Shirov and Teimour Radjabov @@StartBracket@@amongst
others@@EndBracket@@. The main point behind playing 3...e6 is that Black is
now preparing to play the move Nge7, getting ready to recapture on c6 with the
Knight.} 4. Bxc6 {I like this approach a lot! Now our game plan will be to
keep the enemy light squared Bishop as passive as possible! This is generally
a very annoying approach for your opponents because if they are trying to get
creative at any point, we can punish them severly!} bxc6 5. d3 {I decided to
pick this line over 5.b3 that was played in the match for the World Crown in
2012 between Anand and Gelfand. The point of 5.d3 is that we are solidifying
the e4 pawn, and we are staying flexible with the Bishop.You will see that in
some positions it makes sense to go for b3-Bb2.} Ne7 {The old main line.} 6.
Qe2 {The most flexible move in the position! We are waiting to collect more
information about Black's set-up before taking any radical decisions.} Ng6 {We
have to pay attention now because Black is threatening to play e5! and then d6,
to activate the c8 Bishop!} 7. h4 {Black's Knight appears on g6. Can i go h4?
Yes, you can! Well done with the healthy habits, you are a fast learner! This
is a very agressive move generally but you can notice that here is made more
on prophylactical ground.Black was threatening to play e5, and then d6
activating the light squared Bishop. You already know that we need to keep
that guy passive at all costs, so the move comes really natural.} h5 {A
necessity for Black to not get steam-rolled with h5.On hindsight the g5 square
has now been weakened.} 8. e5 {Remember that 3...e6 Rossolimo is all about
keeping the light squared Bishop passive! Black was threatening to play e5 so
if there is not any other way to stop that, we might very well just play e5
ourselves!} f6 {This is known to be the old Main-Line but here you can see
another advantage of having included h4 and h5 on the board:} 9. Qe4 {
Speculating that the Knight is not defended on g6, now Black has to make an
awkward move to defend the Knight.} Kf7 {A sad necessity, but the lesser evil.}
10. Na3 {It is better to go via this route to c4, because if you go for the
other route @@StartBracket@@Nd2-Nc4@@EndBracket@@ the c1 Bishop will be closed
for one move.In our case, it might not make a huge difference, but in other
scenarious, the small details are making the difference.} Ba6 11. Rh3 {Another
benefit of 8.h4! The Rook comes very fast now attacking the enemy King.White
is threatening Ng5.} Qb8 12. Ng5+ {You don't need to be Mikhail Tal to find
this move, but i still think it's a very beautiful shot! Now the freshly
transferred Rook will make the difference!} fxg5 13. Rf3+ {The Rook comes in
with deadly effects.} Nf4 14. hxg5 {We are picking up the Knight next, with a
better position.} *

