1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Seeking to play the Sveshnikov, this move has been the
Main Weapon of the Current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen in his World
Championship Match against Fabiano Caruana in London 2018.} 3. Bb5 {Going for
the Rossolimo Attack! This is considered to be the most painful move for Black
from a theoretical point of view nowadays and also what Fabiano Caruana used
against Magnus Carlsen in their World Championship Match in 2018 to get
promising positions from the opening, even though he could not convert it in
the end. From a practical perspective i think this will help a lot of club
players as well @@StartBracket@@not only the Top Grand Masters@@EndBracket@@
from a number of reasons: -this is a lifetime ever-green opening, always full
of new ideas @@StartBracket@@keeping me busy update the course all the
time@@EndBracket@@ -easy to grasp -it is a plan based opening
@@StartBracket@@you can play this without relying on move by move
preparation@@EndBracket@@} d6 {The main point of this line is to follow 3...d6
up with 4...Bd7 defending the Knight from c6. Although it has ''always been
there'' this line was never getting close to become problematic for White.From
a theoretical point of view it's considered to be quite solid for Black but
White has many interesting tries.For this course i decided to pick:} 4. O-O {
There is no need to take on c6 against 3...d6 unless we are provoked to do so!}
Bd7 5. Re1 {Creating a square for the Bishop on f1.} Nf6 6. h3 {Be very
careful with this! A lot of people tend to be superficial when this early on
in the game thinking like: Um...c3/h3 whatever, we are going to get there
anyways... This is a very common way of thinking and at the end of the day you
might get to the same place once or twice, but at some point you will start
getting punished and you will have to learn it the hard way.I am telling you
cause i've been there...So start with 6.h3! Black will no longer have any Bg4
ideas which is good for us.} a6 7. Bf1 {The safest square, and what we
automatically do against this 3...d6 line.} e5 {Transposing to the Ruy Lopez
structure.} 8. c3 Be7 9. d4 {Grabbing space in the center.} O-O 10. d5 {
Grabbing space, and attacking the Knight.} Na7 11. Nxe5 {A small tactic to win
the Bishop pair.} dxe5 12. d6 {Regaining the piece.} Be6 13. dxe7 {Capturing
the Bishop.} Qxe7 14. Qf3 {Developing the Queen.} Nc6 15. Be3 {Developing the
Bishop, preparing Nd2.} Rfd8 16. Nd2 {White is better with the Bishop Pair.} *

