1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 {Seeking to play the Sveshnikov, this move has been the
Main Weapon of the Current World Champion, Magnus Carlsen in his World
Championship Match against Fabiano Caruana in London 2018.} 3. Bb5 {Going for
the Rossolimo Attack! This is considered to be the most painful move for Black
from a theoretical point of view nowadays and also what Fabiano Caruana used
against Magnus Carlsen in their World Championship Match in 2018 to get
promising positions from the opening, even though he could not convert it in
the end. From a practical perspective i think this will help a lot of club
players as well @@StartBracket@@not only the Top Grand Masters@@EndBracket@@
from a number of reasons: -this is a lifetime ever-green opening, always full
of new ideas @@StartBracket@@keeping me busy update the course all the
time@@EndBracket@@ -easy to grasp -it is a plan based opening
@@StartBracket@@you can play this without relying on move by move
preparation@@EndBracket@@} Qc7 {Together with 3...Qb6, this is a way for Black
to avoid the doubled pawns.The big drawback of this is that White will get a
huge lead in development with simple moves such as 0-0, Nc3,
Bxc6@@StartBracket@@whenever Black will provoke this exchange with ...
a6@@EndBracket@@ and then open up the position with a quick d4!} 4. O-O {Going
for quick development because there is no time to waste when trying to punish
the dubious sidelines!} a6 5. Bxc6 {Now it's the perfect time to take the
Knight because Black has wasted a tempo on playing 4...a6. We will use that as
a weapon to open up the position for a deadly attack in the center!} Qxc6 6. d4
{Opening the position because we have a development advantage.} cxd4 7. Nxd4 {
Not afraid of Qxe4 because you are already familiar with what happens if Black
takes the poisoned pawn.} Qc7 8. Nc3 {Developing the Knight, threatening the
annoying Nd5.} e6 9. Re1 {This subtle Rook move looks very innocent at first,
but it's preparing one of the sneakiest jumps of a Knight that you will ever
witness!} b5 {Black is going for the typical minority attack of the Sicilian
Defense, but get ready to see the coolest way of punishing that!} 10. a4 {
Weakening the Queen-side at first.} b4 {Is always the ambitious reaction that
Black goes for.} 11. Nd5 {But we can go for the surprising Knight jump!Now you
can notice how sneaky of a move 9.Re1 was! This is a very good example of why
to not judge a book by it's cover, the innocent looking Rook on e1 is now
ready to become the main actor of the game!} exd5 12. exd5+ {Opening up the
Rook with deadly effects.} Be7 13. Qg4 {White is threatening to take on g7
next, and together with that, ''innocent'' moves such as Bf4 and Nf5.} *

