1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 {This is the favorite move of the Paulsen/Taimanov players.}
3. b3 {Going for The Westerinen Attack, one of the most underrated openings in
my opinion! This opening does not have the reputation of the Rossolimo, but
that is mainly because people are afraid of 3...b6. The good news is that i
have found a new way of dealing with that particular line, and i am explaining
the nuances down below.} d6 {The point of this move is to prepare Nf6 without
allowing White to get e5 with tempo.} 4. Bb2 {Developing the Bishop.} Nf6 {The
main move for this move order.Black simply wants to play Be7 and castle short.}
5. e5 {The point of this line!We are not going to allow Black to get away with
it.} dxe5 6. Nxe5 {Getting a very active Knight in the center of the board,
and more important, preparing to support it with f4 next!} Nbd7 7. f4 {The big
point of the line, not allowing Black to simply trade our strong Knight and
then finish his development easily.If Black really wants to get rid of our
Knight now, he has to bring our pawn to the e5 square, taking away the f6
square of the Knight, and give us attacking chances on the King-side.If Black
does not take the e5 Knight, we are going to develop our light squared Bishop
on d3, bring the Knight to c4 via a3, and depending on the exact situation,
0-0 with the famous Rook lift Rf3-Rh3 should give us strong attack.} Bd6 8. Na3
{Bringing the Knight to c4 with tempo.} O-O 9. Nac4 {Attacking the Bishop.} Be7
10. Bd3 {Developing the Bishop.} Nxe5 11. fxe5 {Recapturing the piece,
attacking the f6 Knight.} Nd5 12. O-O {Getting our King to safety.} b5 13. Nd6
{Forcing Black to give up the Bishop Pair!} a6 {Would allow White to finish
the game on the spot:} 14. Bxh7+ {A cute way to bring the Queen with tempo.}
Kxh7 15. Nxf7 {Attacking the Queen, threatening Qh5 with mate on h8.} Rxf7 16.
Qh5+ {Finally the Queen joins, with decisive effect.} Kg8 17. Qxf7+ {Picking
up the Rook.} Kh7 18. Rf3 {This is a typical mating construction for the
Westerinen Attack.} *

[Event "?"]
