1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 {This is the favorite move of the Paulsen/Taimanov players.}
3. b3 {Going for The Westerinen Attack, one of the most underrated openings in
my opinion! This opening does not have the reputation of the Rossolimo, but
that is mainly because people are afraid of 3...b6. The good news is that i
have found a new way of dealing with that particular line, and i am explaining
the nuances down below.} d5 {Is a very principled approach by Black to play in
the center because our previous move is a little bit slow.Nevertheless we are
happy to see this move on the board because we are going to have an Isolated
Queen's Pawn type of positions, where we get to trade the light squared
Bishops with 5.Bb5+! Trading the light squared Bishops is helping White a lot,
because the isolated pawn on d5 will be much weaker without Black having a
Bishop on e6 to defend it.Black can try to avoid this scenario by going 5...
Nc6, and not trade the Bishops, but then he is running into concrete problems
after the annoying check 6.Qe2+! You have to be careful with the move orders
as White, but i think the reward is good enough if you do it.} 4. exd5 {Taking
the pawn.} exd5 5. Bb5+ {An important check, threatening to trade the light
squared Bishops and preparing 0-0.} Bd7 {The main move in this position.} 6.
Bxd7+ {Taking the Bishop.} Nxd7 7. O-O {Getting our King to safety.} Bd6 8. Bb2
{Developing the Bishop, attacking g7.} f6 9. d4 {Breaking the center,
preparing to play against the isolani.} Ne7 10. Nc3 {Developing the Knight.}
O-O 11. Nxd5 {A cute tactic to win a pawn.} Nxd5 12. dxc5 {White will win back
the piece with and remain a pawn up.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
