[PlyCount "29"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 {This is the favorite move of the Paulsen/Taimanov players.}
3. b3 {Going for The Westerinen Attack, one of the most underrated openings in
my opinion! This opening does not have the reputation of the Rossolimo, but
that is mainly because people are afraid of 3...b6. The good news is that i
have found a new way of dealing with that particular line, and i am explaining
the nuances down below.} b6 {From a theoretical point of view, this line was
considered to be the refutation of the Westerinen Attack.Black's point is to
develop the Bishop on b7 and then it is going to be quite tricky for White to
defend the e4 pawn without making an awkward move.} 4. d4 {Opening up the
position.The point is to have Nd2 when Black plays Bb7.} cxd4 5. Nxd4 {
Recapturing the pawn.} Bb7 {By far the most natural, and the most played move
in this position.} 6. Nd2 {The good news is that i found this forgotten move
that was barely used in any games! 6.Bd3 used to be the Main-Line, but Black
has no problems whatsoever in that line after 6...Bc5 7.Bb2 and now the strong
7...Qf6! =} Nf6 {The natural move, gives us a plesant position.} 7. Bd3 {
Developing the Bishop, defending the e4 pawn.} d5 {Entering a French structure.
} 8. e5 {Gaining space, and attacking the f6 Knight.} Nfd7 9. Qh5 {Threatening
to take on e6.} g6 10. Qh3 {Sidestepping the attack, keeping an eye on the e6
pawn.} Nc6 11. Nxc6 {Taking the Knight.} Bxc6 12. Bxg6 {A surprising Bishop
sac, now Black is losing a pawn.} fxg6 {Black can try to challenge our idea,
but i doubt that it's going to end well for him!} 13. Qxe6+ Qe7 14. Qxc6 Qxe5+
15. Kd1 {Preparing to play Re1 next, or take the a8 Rook, White is completly
winning thanks to the safer King.} *

