[White "Short and Sweet"]
[Black "2...a6 O'Kelly #3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "23"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 a6 {The O'Kelly Sicilian has arrived on the board!This is a
very tricky variation for White because the Open Sicilian is not working well
here as you can see in the upcoming notes.I used this line myself when i
started chess about 10 years ago with very decent results against club players
because nobody knew how to react against it.Back then it was considered to be
a somewhat doubious line for Black and it was rarely seen in Grand Master
games.Nowdays this line has become very popular even at the 2600+ level mainly
because of Vladislav Artemiev playing it in more than 20 games.Why is this
line becoming more and more popular nowdays?Well, i would say the fact that
you play the Sicilian as Black and White can't go for the Open Sicilian is
pretty powerfull.Back in the days people had a superficial opinion about this
Variation because it was considered that after either 3.c4 or 3.c3 White get's
a free advantage.As theory has advanced, i invite you to go a bit further with
the moves and discover together what is what in the O'Kelly Variation.} 3. c3 {
Going for the delayed Alapin Variation!We are threatening to play d4 and
recapture with the pawn, and create a strong center.The point is that 2.Nf3 is
a common move in the Alapin for White, while 2...a6 by Black is not what you
normally spend your time on!Black has many ways to play here, but the most
critical one is 3...d5, where the inclusion of 2...a6 is not that much felt.In
the other lines White gets a considerable advantage.} e6 4. d4 d5 5. e5 {Is
leading to the French Defence type of structure.The pressence of a6 on the
board is not that big of a deal.Of course it would have been better for Black
to have a choice between Bd7 @@StartBracket@@the Euwe Variation@@EndBracket@@
or other main line with Nge7, so in that way Black is not very flexible.White
still has to come up with a plan to develop and mantain a solid center.I
recommend to put the B on d3 because it's the most active square} Bd7 6. Bd3
Nc6 {As a general strategy White is developing accordingly to the center, the
b1 Knight goes on c3 if Black takes on d4 quickly, but if Black tries to
postpone capturing on d4 i recommend dxc5! solving the problem of the b1
Knight, that will be heading to d4 via Nd2-Nb3-Nbd4.} 7. O-O {Now Black is on
a crossroad.He can choose whether he is going after the d4 pawn, or if he
continues to develop:} Rc8 {Black is threatening to take on d4, and then to
play Nb4, getting rid of our strong Bishop.} 8. dxc5 {At first this might look
like a concession because we are giving up the center, and on top of that we
are helping Black in developing his Bishop.In reality though, things are far
from being that simple for Black.Now let me highlight the positive aspects of
8. dxc5!So what is exactly this move, and why are we doing it?So the big point
is that we are avoiding cxd4 with Nb4, and this way we get to keep the strong
Bishop on d3.On the other hand, the b1 Knight was lacking a good square, and
now this problem has been solved because the Knight is heading to d4 via
Nbd2-Nb3-Nd4.} Bxc5 9. Nbd2 {The Knight is heading to d4.} Nge7 10. Nb3 Ba7 11.
Re1 {Defending the important pawn on e5.} Ng6 {Avoiding The Greek Gift.} 12.
Nbd4 {Always keep in mind advancing your h pawn when the Knight is on g6!} *

