[White "Short and Sweet"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon #1"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "15"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 {Going for the Accelerated Dragon! Little do they know that
we are going to take with the Queen on d4 anyways!} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {As
Hungarian Variation players against 2...d6 it makes very little sense to avoid
this tempting move! From a theoretical point of view this line was considered
a dead draw, but mainly because people played it wrong for a lot of time!
Recently White had found a lot of new ideas that are resulting in to fresh
positions full of life.} Nf6 5. Nc3 {The modern approach, picked up by a lot
of strong Grand Masters.Now White is threatening to play e5 and then if Nc6
happens, White can safely go for Qa4, and there will be no Nd5 available for
Black now since we already developed our Knight to c3!} Nc6 6. Qa4 {This is
the key move!White is threatening to play e5 next, so to stop that, Black has
to play 6...d6@@StartBracket@@the other moves are just inferior@@EndBracket@@
and we can take advantage of the pinned Knight by going 7.e5!} Bg7 7. e5 Nh5 {
A lot of people tend to be stubborn and not go all thr way back to g8 with the
Knight because it is a big loss of tempo, but this allows us to take advantage
of the Knight in a brutal way:} 8. g4 {The Knight is trapped.} *

