1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 {Going for the Accelerated Dragon! Little do they know that
we are going to take with the Queen on d4 anyways!} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {As
Hungarian Variation players against 2...d6 it makes very little sense to avoid
this tempting move! From a theoretical point of view this line was considered
a dead draw, but mainly because people played it wrong for a lot of time!
Recently White had found a lot of new ideas that are resulting in to fresh
positions full of life.} Nf6 5. Nc3 {The modern approach, picked up by a lot
of strong Grand Masters.Now White is threatening to play e5 and then if Nc6
happens, White can safely go for Qa4, and there will be no Nd5 available for
Black now since we already developed our Knight to c3!} Nc6 6. Qa4 {This is
the key move!White is threatening to play e5 next, so to stop that, Black has
to play 6...d6@@StartBracket@@the other moves are just inferior@@EndBracket@@
and we can take advantage of the pinned Knight by going 7.e5!} Bg7 7. e5 Ng8 8.
Bf4 {White simply protects the e5 pawn and continues developing.} Nh6 9. h3 {
A small move that makes sure to stop the Black Knight from jumping on g4.} O-O
10. O-O-O a6 11. g4 {Just making sure that there will be no Nf5.} Rb8 12. Qe4 {
White dominates the whole board.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short and Sweet"]
[Black "Accelerated Dragon #3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "22"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 g6 {Going for the Accelerated Dragon! Little do they know that
we are going to take with the Queen on d4 anyways!} 3. d4 cxd4 4. Qxd4 {As
Hungarian Variation players against 2...d6 it makes very little sense to avoid
this tempting move! From a theoretical point of view this line was considered
a dead draw, but mainly because people played it wrong for a lot of time!
Recently White had found a lot of new ideas that are resulting in to fresh
positions full of life.} Nf6 5. Nc3 {The modern approach, picked up by a lot
of strong Grand Masters.Now White is threatening to play e5 and then if Nc6
happens, White can safely go for Qa4, and there will be no Nd5 available for
Black now since we already developed our Knight to c3!} Nc6 6. Qa4 {This is
the key move!White is threatening to play e5 next, so to stop that, Black has
to play 6...d6@@StartBracket@@the other moves are just inferior@@EndBracket@@
and we can take advantage of the pinned Knight by going 7.e5!} d6 {Is the best
way to play against White's threat of going e5.} 7. e5 {Taking advantage of
the pin!} dxe5 {The main move by far, i never really faced the alternatives,
but i did analysed them in case you might face any.} 8. Nxe5 {Increasing the
pressure on the pinned Knight.} Bd7 {The most played move in this position,
but it gives White a pretty pleasant position with the Bishop Pair.Since the
center is opened, the Bishops are a significant asset here because they can
easily operate on both flanks while the Knight will be struggling.} 9. Nxd7 {
Taking the Bishop Pair, and starting the positional grind!} Qxd7 10. Be3 {The
best square for the Bishop, and preparing to bring Rd1 with tempo.} Bg7 11. Rd1
Qc8 {Is the safest place for the Queen and i covered it in great depth in the
Main Course.} *

